VGuatemala is recovering from a 36-year armed conflict.
p4
aVA conflict that was fought during the Cold War.
p5
aVIt was really just  a small leftist insurgency
p6
aVand a devastating response by the state.
p7
aVWhat we have as a result is 200,000 civilian victims,
p8
aV160,000 of those killed in the communities:
p9
aVsmall children, men, women,  the elderly even.
p10
aVAnd then we have  about 40,000 others, the missing,
p11
aVthe ones we're still looking for today.
p12
aVWe call them the Desaparecidos.
p13
aa(lp14
VNow, 83 percent of the victims  are Mayan victims,
p15
aVvictims that are the descendants
p16
aVof the original inhabitants of  Central America.
p17
aVAnd only about 17 percent are of  European descent.
p18
aVBut the most important thing here is that
p19
aVthe very people who are supposed to  defend us, the police, the military,
p20
aVare the ones that committed most of the crimes.
p21
aa(lp22
VNow the families, they want information.
p23
aVThey want to know what happened.
p24
aVThey want the bodies of their loved ones.
p25
aVBut most of all, what they want is they want you,
p26
aVthey want everyone to know that their loved ones did nothing wrong.
p27
aa(lp28
VNow, my case was that my father received death threats in 1980.
p29
aVAnd we left.
p30
aVWe left Guatemala and we came here.
p31
aVSo I grew up in New York,
p32
aVI grew up in Brooklyn as a matter of fact, and I went to New Utrecht High School
p33
aVand I graduated from Brooklyn College.
p34
aVThe only thing was that
p35
aVI really didn't know what  was happening in Guatemala.
p36
aVI didn't care for it; it was too painful.
p37
aVBut it wasn't till 1995 that I decided to do something about it.
p38
aVSo I went back.
p39
aVI went back to Guatemala,  to look for the bodies,
p40
aVto understand what happened and to look for part of myself as well.
